1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,923
A useful optimization claim needs more than one
favorable number.

2
00:00:03,923 --> 00:00:12,252
ArmQuantLab keeps model size, numerical parity,
protocol, and every measured batch together, including
the two cases where INT8 is slower.

3
00:00:12,902 --> 00:00:14,534
The decision has three parts.

4
00:00:14,534 --> 00:00:15,716
Is the model smaller?

5
00:00:15,716 --> 00:00:17,853
Are outputs still numerically aligned?

6
00:00:17,853 --> 00:00:20,892
And for which batch shapes is latency actually better?

7
00:00:20,892 --> 00:00:24,999
Each answer is tied to the same frozen model hashes
and benchmark report.

8
00:00:25,649 --> 00:00:31,310
The frozen run uses native Arm64, ONNX Runtime's CPU
provider, and one CPU thread.

9
00:00:31,310 --> 00:00:37,730
Each batch gets ten warm-ups, forty measured samples,
and two hundred invocations per sample.

10
00:00:37,730 --> 00:00:41,182
The video does not rerun or replace those metrics.

11
00:00:41,832 --> 00:00:50,663
The workflow creates a deterministic ONNX graph, runs
shape and graph preprocessing, then applies dynamic
per-channel INT8 weight quantization.

12
00:00:50,663 --> 00:00:55,727
FP32 and INT8 receive the same deterministic inputs
before the evidence is frozen.

13
00:00:56,377 --> 00:01:02,349
The preprocessed FP32 model is one million four
hundred forty-six thousand nine hundred eighty-nine
bytes.

14
00:01:02,349 --> 00:01:09,786
INT8 is three hundred seventy-two thousand nine
hundred five bytes, a measured reduction of
seventy-four point two two nine percent.

15
00:01:10,436 --> 00:01:13,361
Compression is not useful if the output diverges.

16
00:01:13,361 --> 00:01:20,047
Across batches one, eight, and thirty-two, cosine
similarity remains above zero point nine nine nine
eight nine.

17
00:01:20,047 --> 00:01:23,271
The report also keeps maximum and mean absolute error.

18
00:01:23,921 --> 00:01:28,096
Batch eight improves p50 latency by one point two
eight two times.

19
00:01:28,096 --> 00:01:35,308
Batch one slows to zero point seven nine five times,
and batch thirty-two slows to zero point six four five
times.

20
00:01:35,308 --> 00:01:37,902
ArmQuantLab keeps all three rows visible.

21
00:01:38,552 --> 00:01:40,630
The speedup profile is non-monotonic.

22
00:01:40,630 --> 00:01:43,214
INT8 wins only at batch eight in this fixture.

23
00:01:43,214 --> 00:01:51,357
That makes the next engineering question concrete:
match optimization to the real batch profile instead
of treating INT8 as automatically faster.

24
00:01:52,007 --> 00:01:57,221
A separate command can process a compatible model the
operator is authorized to use.

25
00:01:57,221 --> 00:02:06,407
It rejects symlinks, external tensor files, oversized
models, unresolved shapes, and unsupported ops, while
keeping the model and derivatives local.

26
00:02:07,057 --> 00:02:13,944
The public fixture collects no hostname, username,
account data, credential, source path, or input value.

27
00:02:13,944 --> 00:02:21,815
It proves reproducible runtime optimization and
numerical parity, not production task accuracy or
universal performance.

28
00:02:22,465 --> 00:02:33,071
The release verifier confirms native Arm64, three
measured batches, a smaller INT8 model, output parity,
model hashes, and a zero-finding public-text privacy
scan.

29
00:02:33,071 --> 00:02:38,081
Six tests also cover deterministic generation and the
compatible-model gates.

30
00:02:38,731 --> 00:02:41,176
ArmQuantLab makes the trade-off reviewable.

31
00:02:41,176 --> 00:02:47,090
The model is substantially smaller, output parity
remains high, one batch is faster, and two are slower.

32
00:02:47,090 --> 00:02:51,127
That honest profile is more useful than a universal
optimization claim.

